    "primary_bug": {
      "id": "primary",
      "summary": "The new fill loop in LineBuffer::fill reads repeatedly until the caller's buffer is full (`while !self.free_buffer().is_empty() { let readlen = rdr.read(...)?; if readlen==0 { break } self.end += readlen; }`), which breaks --line-buffered / streaming: line-buffered mode must yield what it can read immediately, not block waiting for a full buffer. Regressed real streaming use such as `journalctl -f | rg --line-buffered`.",
      "file": "crates/searcher/src/line_buffer.rs",
      "locus": "fill(): the added inner `while !self.free_buffer().is_empty()` read-until-full loop (~L416-421)",
      "must_flag": "A reviewer catches this if it flags that packing the whole buffer across multiple reads defeats --line-buffered / prompt streaming (or otherwise identifies the read-loop as changing streaming/latency behavior).",
      "source": "revert PR #3195 ('searcher: fix regression with --line-buffered flag'), regression issue #3194 ('Line buffering appears broken in 15.0.0')",
      "difficulty": "subtle — requires reasoning about line-buffered/streaming semantics; the maintainer himself merged it and reverted only after a user bug report. Expect low recall; a genuine catch here is a strong signal."
    },
